<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,970,1319]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,1078,1103]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Description &amp; Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 
<quantity box="[638,722,1078,1102]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="29.0">29 mm</quantity>
, a little smaller than 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1092,1078,1103]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buxtoni">
<emphasis box="[974,1092,1078,1103]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">L. buxtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Forewing palebrown, with a smooth, black line from apex to basal area of forewings, highlighted proximally by a broad white band (
<figureCitation box="[1322,1391,1114,1138]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 10" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[243,1351,220,1911]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[226,1360,187,1932]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 10. Adult moths of Lithostege Hübner (left column, a: upperside, right column, b: underside). 6. L. stadiei (3, type locality, NW Iran); 7. L. obliquata (3, Karakumi, Turkmenistan); 8. L. bosporaria (3, Kirikkale, Central Turkey); 9. L. usgentaria (Ƥ, Herat, W Afghanistan); 10. L. witzenmanni (Ƥ, Ghotor, NW Iran). Scale bar: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279202/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[1375,1391,1114,1138]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). In the somewhat similar 
<taxonomicName box="[400,514,1150,1175]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buxtoni">
<emphasis box="[400,514,1150,1175]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">L. buxtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this line is strongly waved distally and terminates at the middle of the hind margin. Hindwings white, without any pattern. Male genitalia highly similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1221,1187,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buxtoni">
<emphasis box="[1107,1221,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">L. buxtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1237,1314,1186,1210]" captionStart="FIGURES 35 – 38" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1881,1904]" captionTargetBox="[235,1352,194,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[226,1360,173,1860]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 35 – 38. Lithostege Hübner: Male genitalia &amp; details of abdominal integument. 35. L. distinctata (gen. prep. 1089 H. R.; Dushak Mt., Turkmenistan), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view; 36. L. buxtoni (gen. prep. 1066 H. R.; Kazerun, S Iran), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view; 37. L. stadiei (photo of L. Lehmann; type locality, NW Iran), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view; 38. L. obliquata (gen. prep. 1087 H. R.; Ashkhabad), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view, c: 8 th tergite (lateral margins slightly curved up). Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279208/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[1284,1314,1186,1210]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="37.0">37</number>
</figureCitation>
), but basal process of valve narrower, with almost pointed tip, terminal half of uncus gradually tapering towards apex, the latter not truncate. Aedeagus shorter, almost straight. Female unknown.
</paragraph>
